segments.text: One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.
This is the 27th, 9th of May, and we're at 2100 Vinewood, Owen Word, in Bryan, and I have the pleasure and honor of recording the A&M Memories of Joe Hanover.
Mr. Hanover, as we begin, introduce yourself to anyone who will hear this tape or read the typed version.
Describe family background, growing up, what did your mom and dad do, where'd y'all live, where'd you go to high school, all about yourself before you go to A&M.
Okay, I'm Joe.
I go by Joe G. Hanover.
because there were two Johanovers and we had to distinguish between them.
In 1925, my family moved to the little village of Wheelock, which is about 20 miles northeast of Bryan.
My father was a cattle farmer, had sharecroppers on the place.
I went to grammar school in Wheelock.
through the ninth grade, I guess it was, and at that time the high school had to go to Franklin.
We did not have eleven grades in Wheelock, so they were bused to Franklin.
I did my tenth and eleventh grades in Franklin.
Graduated from there in 1936.
How many in your senior class?
At Franklin?
Oh, I imagine 20 maybe.
And as you were thinking about what to do after high school, what led you to go to college?
I knew when I went to college what I wanted to do, Haskell.
No, but who encouraged you to go to college?
I knew what I wanted to do because back in the late 20s and early 30s, the highway department was rebuilding the old San Antonio Road.
And I followed the survey crew up and down that road as far as I could from my home.
and said to everybody, I want to be a civil engineer when I go to college.
And that was run by a man by the name of Bill Cape.
C-A-P-E?
C-A-P-E, who was, I believe, city manager of Bryan at one time, and ultimately was city manager of Houston.
And he was an A&M graduate.
And that's where I got the idea of what I wanted to do when I got, when I went to college.
Because I'm assuming that your parents were not college graduates.
They were not.
And I'm assuming that A&M was your choice because you knew about it and knew about its strengths in signal engineering.
And it was close to home.
Now you were born where?
McGregor, Texas.
In McGregor.
That's about 20 miles west of Waco.
Yeah.
Now why did your family move from McGregor to Wheelock?
Well, my father was in the cotton gin business in McGregor, along with the grain business.
He and another gentleman up there, and in 1923 or 1924, I've forgotten which it was, his gin burned.
And he told his partner that if he'd take what insurance they had and take the business, that he would pull out of it and come to Wheelock and help his father manage his farm.
He had about 1,400 acres there, as I said, with sharecroppers and ran cattle and needed some help.
So that's why we went there.
What were the money crops on that 1,400 acres?
Cotton and corn.
Cotton and corn.
Cotton and corn.
That's only two things they raised.
But y'all also had chickens and a few hogs and garden and orchard and everything.
Right.
Had everything that you'd in the kitchen.
Before you came to A&M to enroll, you had visited the campus?
Yeah, I had been to that campus a number of times.
My dad used the veterinary hospital for his animals if he had to have something to...
So many times I visited the campus with him through the veterinary department.
And what impression did those visits to A&M make on you and your family?
Well, of course, I knew I wanted to go there in the first place and
And the more we went there, the more I liked it and the more infatuated with it was, I guess you might say, and also knew of these engineers that preceded me that I knew of.
Now 1936 was a tough year financially.
What kind of money did you have to help finance your freshman year?
I had one cow and sold one calf every year and I lived at home.
My grandfather had an old 1929 Chevrolet and he told me if I could keep it running and keep some people riding with me to help pay the expenses, I could drive back and forth and live at home.
So I would get up every morning, help milk seven cows, drive to A&M, go to school, take the passengers that worked at A&M.
The AAA had employees, as the Extension Service had employees, and then two or three students.
I always had a carload, and they shared my expenses with me.
What time did you get up?
Before daylight.
Oh, high school I must have gotten up, oh, 530 or so.
And you'd milk those seven cattle.
We used to milk seven.
And then... Had to help feed the horses and mules, eat my breakfast, get dressed and drive 20 miles to A&M.
And it took about how long to drive that 20 miles?
About 45 minutes at that time.
You came down what is now... Old San Antonio Road.
OSR.
OSR.
And then we came through what we call the Cameron Ranch Road, which is now 2223.
It cuts across from San Antonio Road and comes in on the Table Road just east of Bryan.
About how many riders did you have?
Well, it was a six passenger car and I always had five besides myself.
Okay, so you filled it up.
Filled it up.
Did they pay for anything other than gas?
No, they didn't.
In fact, I would charge them just a specified amount each time, which was just to cover my expenses.
So you didn't make any profit on that?
No, I didn't, not really.
first came down to how did you get admitted?
What was the admissions process there?
I don't even know.
I've thought about that a lot of times.
I don't know.
I really don't know how I got admitted.
Don't know what the process was.
Right.
You had to be officially in the Corps.
but you were a day student.
Describe how... Well, there was day student organizations in the Corps.
I belonged to a day student Coast Artillery outfit.
And even though I was taking engineering, the reason I was in the Coast Artillery, I was advised that

they liked the engineers in the Coastal Artillery because all of our spotting and projecting and manning tables and all were calculated with slide rules and tables to project the, I mean to anticipate the projectile trajectory and how far they'd go and this sort of thing.
So I was encouraged to get in the Coastal Artillery.
Now had you made good grades in high school?
I did.
I guess above average.
What kind of math did you take in high school?
Do you remember how far up the ladder you went?
took trigonometry, took no calculus, took trigonometry and several arithmetics or whatever they had.
Solid geometry and playing.
We're talking about the math you had had in high school.
I had geometry and
Do you remember what sciences you had?
Did you have physics?
Yeah.
No, I had no physics.
Chemistry?
No chemistry, unfortunately.
And that made it tough at A&M.
When did you learn to use the slide rule?
At A&M.
At A&M, okay.
No, I didn't have none of that in high school.
When you came down here to enroll,
Who advised you what courses to take your freshman year?
Well, there must have been some advisors where I was enrolling, because they're the ones that suggested I get into Coast Artillery, and I'm sure they're the ones that advised me what to take.
You know, Haskell, that's been so far back.
I hear you.
Now you were issued a whole bunch of uniforms.
Yeah.
And so when you came each day you wore your core uniforms.
Either that or your fatigues.
I had, you know, we had sort of coverall like things that we wore on certain days.
Right.
Describe, describe a typical class day.
You got up what time and did what and where did you, when you came to campus, where did you park?
There was one parking place on the campus.
Only day students were allowed on the campus with a car.
And it was... Well, there used to be a big water tower up behind the power plant.
On the north side of the campus?
Yes.
There was a big parking lot right there, and that's where we parked.
We'd come in in the morning, I would go by and let the workers out, and that's the only way you could drive on the campus.
In fact, time or two I got a ticket for driving on the campus before they knew I was authorized to take these workers.
And come back and I'd park.
Well, if I didn't have a class, I'd go to the library and study, or study in the car.
And if I had as much as two hours, I worked.
I had a student labor job with the landscape department.
There was a fellow by the name of Horsley that managed the student labor, and I was fortunate enough to get a student labor job.
Was it Graham Horsley?
Wendell Horsley?
Wendell Horsley.
Wendell Horsley.
And I worked for the landscape department, and I did everything in the world.
Dug in the flower beds, pushed lawn mowers, picked the mealybugs off the
the big flowers in that greenhouse.
What were some of the special new projects?
Was the grand driveway going out to Texas Avenue
Were those trees already set out when you got here?
Some of them.
Some of them were set out after I was there.
And I helped set out trees.
I helped dig them in the...
They grew their own out in the nursery.
And part of the job at times would go out and dig them.
Where was the nursery?
It was out... Well, if you come...
It's...
I don't know what street.
Was it west of the tracks?
No, no, it was east of the tracks.
It was back toward Bryan on the big boulevard that comes out to University from Bryan and stops there by the big engineering building.
Back on that road, back behind those
buildings that they built out there where the students used to live.
Okay, back at College View.
Yeah, right.
That's where a lot of the nursery was.
Was a young man named Bob Rucker working?
Yes.
I worked with Bob.
Bob lived in the greenhouse.
That's what I heard.
Bob lived in the greenhouse and got part of his expenses paid by looking after the greenhouse.
Because he was from Franklin.
That's right.
I knew him in Franklin.
He was a year or two ahead of me, but Bob Rucker was a, he was a special sort of a student with the landscape department.
Describe Mr. Horsley and his manner of working with people.
Well, I think he just came there about the time I did.
He was, he was new there.
I don't know whether he came for that purpose or whether that was settled off onto him about the student labor.
But he was a real nice fellow as far as the students were concerned, but well liked.
We all thought he treated us very well.
He didn't have any of the management of the labor done.
He was more of the administrative part of the student labor.
What was the pay of you, of you as a student laborer?
Thirty cents an hour.
And about how many hours a week did you work?
Well, I could work, I could work 40 hours a month.
And I could work anytime I had as much as two hours.
They wouldn't let you work one hour, but I could work any time I had two hours.
And did you do that all four years?
I did.
And I sort of had the insight on that labor.
Mr. Hensel, who was head of the landscape department, was a friend of my daddy's sister.
And she told him I needed a job down there.
And so he was...
managed to get me on to the landscape student labor.
Did you do that your first semester?
I did from the time I started.
All four years?
Plus all three summers.
See my writers had to be there in the summer and I usually took one or two courses less in the long term and I'd pick it up in the summer because I could work in the summer.
I could make a little more in the summer as I remember.
As far as you can recall, about how much did it cost for you to go to A&M then?
I can tell you pretty close.
Okay.
Out of pocket, Haskell.
Out of pocket.
For four years and three summers, about $500.
Plus your books?
Or were the books included in that?
Well, that's what it took for me to go to A&M.
And how much of that did you earn?
Oh, well, it's about $40 a month.
I mean $30, let's see, $30 a month.
And see, that would be what, oh, 180 or whatever $30 a month would come out to.
See, that was part of what I spent.
In other words, over and above that, it was my $500, as I'm talking about.
So I went to school pretty economically.
Now, as you began your college, did your mother or your dad or anyone else give you any instructions?
Well, they'd give me instructions before I started.
Oh, I had a very, very encouraging parents, not only when I got to college, but high school, church, community, the whole business.
It didn't take much encouraging.
I knew what I wanted, and they furnished
all the backup that I needed.
My dad told me, when I got ready to go to A&M, he said, I don't have money to send you to A&M.
Didn't have any money to send me.
And said, with this automobile, I'll furnish your meals at home, of course.
Mother will fix your lunch.
I took a lunch.
Didn't have to buy lunch down there.
And he said, if you can make it, well, that'll be fine.
We'd be happy.
What was the typical lunch that you brought?
A couple of sandwiches.
Made out of what?
Homemade bread.
And what kind of meat?
Sausage that they'd made at home, or ham, or bacon that they had killed the hogs on.
And where would you eat that lunch?
Sitting in the car.
In the car.
Did you drink anything?
I brought water, just brought water from home.
And then there was fountains in the
It was right next to what then was called the Mechanical Engineering Building.
I don't know what it is now.
And then there was a cotton mill on the backside of it over there too.
So we could use that for our restrooms and water fountains.
Now where would you change your clothes to get out of your uniforms to put on your work clothes?
I'd do mine over at the landscape building, where the flowers were grown.
The horticulture?
No, the landscape building, where Robert Rucker had his room over there.
What do you call it where you keep flowers?
Greenhouse?
Greenhouse.
That's what I'm trying to think of.
Over at the greenhouse.
Just bring them along in the car and hang them up.
All right, so you would leave home 6.30?
Tried to leave by 7.
Because nobody had to be there before 8.
Then go to class.
Generally, did you do your landscape work in the afternoons?
Whenever I had two hours.
It could be morning or afternoon.
Now, as officially a member of the Coast Artillery Company, when did that company gather on campus?
Did you all have to fall out?
One afternoon, on a Thursday afternoon.
And what did you do that afternoon?
Well, we'd go to the armory.
They had a six-inch gun down there, had the rifles, had an indoor rifle range, and then had class work on artillery, artillery spotting, projectiles, the tables and all for the artillery.
And that's, it was, and then we'd go out and do close order drill out on the drill field.
Now did your outfit have a nickname?
Don't believe.
Your Coast Artillery Company?
Don't believe.
I don't remember it if we did.
Was it, what was it, C-1?
What was its, did it have a designation?
Well, they were A, B, Company A, I mean, Battery.
We were Batteries.
Battery.
What Battery were y'all?
Do you remember?
Well, it was the day student.
Seemed to me like it was D Battery.
About how many were in that outfit?
I expect there was 75 probably, right, at Haskell.
Did y'all get hazed?
I didn't, being a day student.
See, I'm not living on the campus.
I was never involved in hazing at all.
And were, now was everybody in the company a day student?
In that particular company.
That's what I mean.
That was a day student company.
Was there a nickname?
Were y'all called Day Ducks?
Yes, that's what they were.
How did you learn Aggie slang, Aggie traditions, and all that?
Where did they?
Just by association, I guess.
Of course, not living in the dormitory, I didn't get a lot of that that some of them did.
Did you have to whip out to upperclassmen as you walked across the campus?
Oh, yeah.
You had to yes sir and no sir and all that, you know.
Describe as much as you can
The courses you had that first year, what were some of the key courses and the key teachers?
I had English, two courses of English, first and second English.
I had algebra, algebra one and two.
I believe the first year I had trigonometry.
And then somewhere down the line I had two terms of calculus.
I don't know what year.
That probably was the second, maybe.
What about physics?
I had physics.
I'd be physical the first year, if I'm not mistaken.
And that physics and chemistry really was tough on me, not having it in high school.
About how big were those classes?
Oh, 20 or 25.
Do you remember any of the teachers?
Oh, I do.
Please describe them.
Okay.
I remember my chemistry teacher.
His name was Koenig.
K-O-E-N-I-G?
Yes.
And he lived here in Bryan, and there's some streets named for him here.
He owned some property.
He was my freshman chemistry teacher.
I knew I was going to fail from the time I started.
He had a brogue, he was a German, deep brogue, and he taught to the level of students who'd had it in high school, and I knew I wasn't going to make it.
But I stayed with it, I guess I learned something, and then turned right around and took it in summer school and made a B on it.
But that's the first
First course I ever failed, high school or any other time.
But the guys that, you know, that had had chemistry, oh, they could answer all the questions, you know, and as I say, I knew I was going to fail.
What about English?
Do you remember who taught that?
I got my old longhorn out trying to figure out my English teacher.
He was from Bryan here.
And I can see him, but I can't tell you what his name was.
One of them.
What about math?
Well, the math teachers were... Can't come up with them either, Haskell.
I don't know why I can't think of that English teacher.
I can see him just as plain.
But I was not too good an English student either.
I passed.
In fact, I'll tell you one teacher I do remember, a history teacher named Count Shigariff.
Have you ever heard of him?
Yes, I have.
Describe him, please.
He was the funniest guy you ever did see.
I was told he was an escapee from a Red Russian organization of some type.
And he was comical.
And he had a...
When he talked, he rolled his R's.
If he called my name, it's Mr. Hanover.
And he'd roll it big, you know.
And he would threaten you.
At that time, as you probably know, the girls who were favorites of A&M were in CIA up in Denton, the girls' college.
Well, if you couldn't answer a question correctly, he was going to send you to CIA.
Would it hurt if I say something here?
No.
But remember, the circumstance is going to cut your nuts out first.
Now, what history was this?
World history or American history or European?
I guess it was American history, yeah.
And you'd answer incorrectly.
Where'd you get that answer, Mr. Hannibal?
Got it out of the book.
The book's no damn good.
Throw it out the window.
And some of them throw the damn thing out the window.
He's one that I'll never forget.
I remember one of my civil engineer teachers named Richie, Cuball Richie, they called him.
And they called him Cuball because he always erased the board with his fist like that, and then he'd rub it all over his bald head.
So he was called Cuball Richie.
And he was comical.
He would get up and illustrate a stress.
he'd push against the wall till his feet would slide on the floor.
Or if he was talking about a beam, he'd run over like this, this beam, and that beam.
Just comical.
So those kinds of people, I remember them, remember the names.
Hey, you went to class every day?
Every day.
Five and a half days.
Yes, yes.
On Saturday at the noon.
Now, normally you left campus about what time at the end of the day?
After five.
After five.
The workers got off at five.
And you'd head home, and what chores did you have to do at home when you got back?
Well, had to milk those same cows again.
They had to be milked twice a day, seven days a week, you know.
I think that about the routine when I got home, usually Mother would have a little snack for us or something.
And then we'd bring in the wood or whatever the chores there had to be.
Then we'd try to get the milking done before dark and then come in and eat supper.
And my routine was after supper I'd lie down and sleep 15 minutes.
And then I could study till 10, 10.30, 11 and get up the next morning reasonably.
What kind of study space did you have at home?
Had a nice living room, but until I was a junior, had to study by kerosene lamp.
Y'all didn't have any electricity?
No electricity.
Did you have a telephone?
Yeah.
It's right around on the wall around here.
What was the phone number?
Two longs and a short.
You were on a party line?
On a party line.
About how many were on that party line?
Twenty or thirty, everybody in the community just about.
And you all lived how far from the paved road?
Well, they paved the old San Antonio Road in late 29, I mean in late 30s, late 20s.
Your family's place was on the OSR?
About 1,500 feet back from the road, but we were on the old San Antonio Road.
How far to Wheelock?
Two miles.
And how far to Franklin?
It was 11 miles to Franklin from Wheelive.
Then I'd go to bed and, well, take a bath and go to bed.
And we had running water in the house.
My dad had arranged some years before to have two elevated cisterns, he called it, and a windmill.
And when you didn't have any wind, though, we didn't have any water.
And we arranged a place out in the garden behind the garage with a sprinkler and a hose, and that's where we took our bath out there, even in pretty cold weather.
And the temperature of the water was the temperature of the weather.
That's exactly right.
Then on Sunday, church?
Yes.
Where'd y'all go?
We are.
Which church?
Methodist.
The church at Wheat Lock was a union church.
One Sunday the Baptist preacher, next Sunday the Methodist.
And so the crowd was the same.
My mother was a devout Baptist, and I was baptized a Baptist.
But when you went to church, you didn't know who was what.
